(43, 21, 1, 43, 6, 1, 1, 'the sea of Tiberias', 'Connection of Locations', 'Both passages mention the sea of Tiberias, linking the locations of Jesus'' ministry. This connection highlights the geographical significance of the sea in the narrative.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 40, 28, 16, 16, NULL, 'Disciples Gather at Sea', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the disciples in a specific location after Jesus'' resurrection. John 21:1 mentions the sea of Tiberias, while Matthew 28:16 refers to a mountain in Galilee, indicating a significant post-resurrection meeting.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 43, 6, 23, 23, 'sea of Tiberias', 'Connection Between Tiberias References', 'Both passages emphasize the Sea of Tiberias, linking the location of Jesus'' post-resurrection appearance to the earlier miracle of feeding the multitude. This connection highlights the significance of Tiberias in the ministry of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 40, 26, 32, 32, NULL, 'Resurrection and Galilee Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' post-resurrection appearances. John 21:1 describes Jesus showing himself to the disciples at the sea of Tiberias, which aligns with Matthew 26:32''s mention of his intention to meet them in Galilee after his resurrection.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 1, 41, 16, 7, 7, 'shewed he himself', 'Post-Resurrection Appearances', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' appearances to the disciples after his resurrection. John 21:1 mentions Jesus showing himself again, while Mark 16:7 indicates he will meet them in Galilee.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 40, 4, 21, 22, 'sons of Zebedee', 'Discipleship and Calling', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Simon Peter and the sons of Zebedee, highlighting their roles as key disciples. This connection illustrates the continuity of their discipleship from the initial calling to their later gatherings with Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 43, 4, 46, 46, 'Cana in Galilee', 'Connection through Cana of Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Cana of Galilee, linking the disciples'' presence in John 21:2 to Jesus'' earlier miracle in John 4:46. This connection highlights the significance of Cana as a location in Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 6, 19, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Names and Places', 'This connection highlights the presence of specific names in both passages. In John 21:2, the names of disciples are mentioned, while Joshua 19:28 lists geographical locations, suggesting a thematic link between individuals and their respective places.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 2, 42, 5, 10, 10, 'sons of Zebedee', 'Discipleship of Peter and Zebedee', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Simon Peter and the sons of Zebedee, highlighting their roles as disciples. This connection illustrates their partnership in fishing and their subsequent calling to become ''fishers of men.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 42, 5, 5, 5, 'caught nothing', 'Fishing and Fruitlessness', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of fishing all night and catching nothing. This connection highlights the theme of struggle and the call to trust in Jesus'' word.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 40, 4, 18, 20, 'fishing', 'Fishing as a Metaphor', 'Both passages emphasize fishing, linking Peter''s initial profession to his later calling. The act of fishing in both contexts serves as a metaphor for discipleship and evangelism.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 53, 3, 7, 9, NULL, 'Work and Labor Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and effort in both passages. In John 21:3, Peter and others worked all night fishing but caught nothing, while in 2 Thessalonians 3:7-9, Paul emphasizes working with labor and travail to set an example.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 52, 2, 9, 9, NULL, 'Labour and Night Work Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of laboring through the night. In John 21:3, the disciples fish all night without success, while in 1 Thessalonians 2:9, Paul speaks of laboring night and day to preach the gospel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 12, 6, 1, 7, 'I go a fishing', 'Theme of Going and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the act of going forth to seek something. In John 21:3, Peter and others go fishing, while in 2 Kings 6:1-7, the sons of the prophets go to the Jordan to gather materials.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 46, 3, 7, 7, 'I go a fishing', 'Fishing and Spiritual Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of effort in both passages. In John 21:3, the disciples'' fishing symbolizes human effort, while 1 Corinthians 3:7 emphasizes that true growth comes from God, not human actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 3, 44, 18, 3, 3, 'I go a fishing', 'Connection of Occupation and Activity', 'This connection highlights the theme of work and occupation in both passages. In John 21:3, Peter and others return to fishing, while in Acts 18:3, Paul stays with tentmakers, emphasizing their shared craft.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 43, 20, 14, 14, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not recognizing Jesus at first. In each instance, the disciples and Mary encounter Jesus but do not initially know who He is.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 42, 24, 15, 16, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' inability to recognize Jesus. In John, the disciples ''knew not that it was Jesus,'' while in Luke, ''their eyes were holden that they should not know him.'' This connection highlights a theme of divine concealment in recognizing the resurrected Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 41, 16, 12, 12, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Post-Resurrection Appearances', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus appearing to his disciples in different forms after his resurrection. Both passages describe moments when the disciples did not immediately recognize Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 4, 42, 24, 31, 31, 'knew not that it was Jesus', 'Recognition of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the moment of recognition of Jesus by the disciples. In John 21:4, the disciples do not initially recognize Jesus, while in Luke 24:31, their eyes are opened, and they know him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 50, 4, 19, 19, 'any meat', 'Provision and Supply Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of provision, as both passages address the idea of needs being met. In John 21:5, the disciples express a lack of food, while Philippians 4:19 assures that God will supply all needs.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 50, 4, 11, 13, 'have ye any meat?', 'Contentment in Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of contentment in both passages. In John 21:5, the disciples express a lack of physical sustenance, while Philippians 4:11-13 discusses being content regardless of circumstances, including hunger.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 19, 37, 3, 3, NULL, 'Provision and Trust in God', 'This connection highlights the theme of being fed and trusting in God for sustenance. In both passages, the idea of being provided for is central, with Jesus asking if the disciples have food and the Psalmist encouraging trust in the Lord to ensure one will be fed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 42, 24, 41, 43, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus and Food', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus asking for food, highlighting his physical presence and interaction with his disciples after resurrection. This connection illustrates the continuity of Jesus'' ministry and his concern for their needs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 58, 13, 5, 5, 'have ye any meat?', 'Contentment and Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of reliance on Jesus for provision and contentment. In both passages, the disciples'' lack of meat and the call to be content with what one has reflect a deeper trust in Jesus'' presence and care.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 5, 62, 2, 13, 13, 'Children', 'Connection of Children in Faith', 'This connection highlights the term ''children'' used in both passages. In John 21:5, Jesus addresses the disciples as ''Children,'' while 1 John 2:13 refers to ''little children'' in a spiritual context, emphasizing their relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 42, 5, 4, 7, 'cast the net on the right side', 'Miraculous Catch of Fish', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous catch of fish following Jesus'' command to cast nets. In each instance, the disciples experience an overwhelming abundance of fish, demonstrating the power of Jesus'' word.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 21, 6, 44, 2, 41, 41, 'ye shall find', 'Miraculous Provision and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous provision leading to abundance. In John 21:6, the disciples experience a miraculous catch of fish, while in Acts 2:41, the result of Peter''s preaching leads to the addition of three thousand souls, showcasing divine abundance in both instances.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
